'''Murahi Shrine''' ('''Murahi Jinja'''; むらひじんじゃ) is a Shinto shrine located in {{ill|lt=Tochigi Prefecture|Q44843|qid=Q44843|1=Tochigi Prefecture}}{{ill|lt=Tochigi City|Q44830|qid=Q44830|1=Tochigi (city)}}. Under the {{ill|lt=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|qid=Q712534|lt=former shrine ranking system|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}, it was classified as a village shrine (gōsha). It claims the title of the Third Shrine of Shimotsuke Province.

=== History ===
According to shrine tradition, on {{ill|lt=Taika|Q1077930|qid=Q1077930|1=Taika (era)}} 2 ({{ill|lt=646|Q33285|qid=Q33285|1=646}}) {{ill|lt=September 29 (lunar calendar)|Q840263|qid=Q840263|lt=September 29|1=September 29 (Lunisolar)}}{{Sfn|Kazayama|1903|p=59}}, {{ill|lt=Kumano Gongen|Q11568925|qid=Q11568925|lt=the Kumano deity|1=Kumano Gongen}} and {{ill|lt=Sannō Gongen|Q11470054|qid=Q11470054|lt=the Hie deity|1=Sannō Gongen}} ({{ill|qid=Q10935105|lt=Ōyamakui no Kami|Q10935105|qid=Q10935105|1=Oyamakui no Kami}}) were invited and enshrined{{Sfn|Tochigi City Board of Education|2014|p=21}}{{Sfn|Iwafune Town Board of Education|1974|p=14}}{{Sfn|Ishihara|1964|p=198}}. Ōyamakui no Kami is the deity of {{ill|lt=Mount Hiei|Q748040|qid=Q748040|1=Mount Hiei}}, and its enshrinement here has been noted in connection with the nearby {{ill|lt=Daijiji (Tochigi City)|Q11435473|qid=Q11435473|lt=Onodera-san Daijiji Temple|1=Daiji-ji Temple}}{{Sfn|Murakami|1967|p=121}}. The surrounding areas—{{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Onodera|UNKNOWN|lt=Onodera}}, {{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Kamioka|UNKNOWN|lt=Kamioka}}, {{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Shimo-oka|UNKNOWN|lt=Shimo-oka}}, {{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Mitani|UNKNOWN|lt=Mitani}}, {{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Niisato|UNKNOWN|lt=Niisato}}, {{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Furue|UNKNOWN|lt=Furue}}, {{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Shimotsuhara|Q109369623|qid=Q109369623|lt=Shimotsuhara|1=Shimotsuhara}}, {{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Tatamioka|UNKNOWN|lt=Tatamioka}}, Komaba (now part of {{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Shizu|Q11662858|qid=Q11662858|lt=Shizu|1=Iwafunemachi Shizuka}}), and {{ill|lt=Iwafune-chō Washinosu|Q11676262|qid=Q11676262|lt=Washinosu|1=Iwafunemachi Washinosu}}—were collectively called the “Ten Villages of Onodera,” and the shrine is said to have been founded as their guardian shrine{{Sfn|Ishihara|1964|p=198}}.

In {{ill|lt=Daido (Japan)|Q1373191|qid=Q1373191|lt=Daido|1=Daidō}} 2 ({{ill|lt=807|Q30016|qid=Q30016|1=807}}), the enshrined deity {{ill|UNKNOWN|qid=Q317997|lt=Hondawake no Mikoto|1=Emperor Ōjin}}, originally worshiped at the Hachiman Shrine of Onoguchi in {{ill|lt=Minagawa Village|Q11580946|qid=Q11580946|1=Minagawa}}, which had been merged, was welcomed as the principal deity. Furthermore, during the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Seiwa|Q349243|qid=Q349243|1=Emperor Seiwa}} ({{ill|lt=858|Q30371|qid=Q30371|1=858}}–{{ill|lt=876|Q23815|qid=Q23815|1=876}}), the Hachiman deity that had been invited to Hachimanzawa in Minagawa Village was, during the reign of {{ill|lt=Emperor Kōkō|Q440518|qid=Q440518|1=Emperor Kōkō}} ({{ill|lt=884|Q23895|qid=Q23895|1=884}}–{{ill|lt=887|Q25010|qid=Q25010|1=887}}), merged into Murahi Shrine on the grounds that its original site was impure{{Sfn|Tochigi City Board of Education|2014|p=21}}{{Sfn|Iwafune Town Board of Education|1974|p=14}}{{Sfn|Ishihara|1964|p=198}}.

In {{ill|lt=Tengyō|Q1327340|qid=Q1327340|1=Tengyō}} 2 ({{ill|lt=939|Q23422|qid=Q23422|1=939}}), {{ill|lt=Fujiwara no Hidesato|Q1136623|qid=Q1136623|1=Fujiwara no Hidesato}}, who went on to subdue {{ill|lt=Taira no Masakado|Q1207652|qid=Q1207652|1=Taira no Masakado}}, is said to have prayed here for victory{{Sfn|Tochigi City Board of Education|2014|p=21}}{{Sfn|Iwafune Town Board of Education|1974|p=14}}. There is also a theory that the shrine itself was founded by Hidesato. In Kōno Morihiro’s *Shimotsuke Kokushi*, it is stated that Hidesato, as lord of {{ill|lt=Karasawayama Castle|Q11418602|qid=Q11418602|1=Karasawa Castle}}, founded Murahi Shrine about one *ri* away to the northeast (the demon gate) to protect the castle{{Sfn|Kōno|1893|p=12}}{{Sfn|Suzuka|1902|p=294}}. Some sources describe this as a “reconstruction”{{Sfn|Tochigi Prefectural Education History Compilation Committee|1957|p=428}}.

From the medieval period onward, the shrine received devotion from the {{ill|lt=Shimotsuke Onodera clan|Q16141519|qid=Q16141519|1=Shimotsuke Onodera clan}} and the {{ill|lt=Sano clan|Q11385058|qid=Q11385058|1=Sano clan}}, lords of Karasawayama Castle{{Sfn|Tochigi City Board of Education|2014|p=21}}{{Sfn|Iwafune Town Board of Education|1974|p=14}}. During the Edo period, it was also revered by merchants of Tochigi Town, where {{ill|lt=Tochigi-juku|Q30926264|qid=Q30926264|1=Tochigi-juku}} was established{{Sfn|Higano|1966|p=50}}. In front of the shrine buildings stands a pair of Oribe lanterns dedicated in {{ill|lt=Kyōhō|Q1145048|qid=Q1145048|1=Kyōhō}} 11, 12th month ({{ill|lt=1726|Q6936|qid=Q6936|1=1726}} December or January of the following year) by the Noguchi family, hemp wholesalers of “Tsukegi Kamimachi” (present-day {{ill|lt=Mannmachi (Tochigi City)|Q11353890|qid=Q11353890|lt=Mannmachi|1=Yorozuchō}} in Tochigi City){{Sfn|Tochigi City History Compilation Committee|1978|pp=527–528}}.

In {{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 5 ({{ill|lt=1872|Q7753|qid=Q7753|1=1872}}), the shrine was designated a village shrine (gōsha) under the {{ill|lt=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines|Q712534|qid=Q712534|1=Modern system of ranked Shinto shrines}}{{Sfn|Meiji Shrine Records Compilation Office|1912|p=46}}.

=== Cultural Properties ===
=== Important Cultural Property (National Designation) ===
* '''Main Hall'''
: Built in {{ill|lt=Tenbun|Q1192853|qid=Q1192853|1=Tenbun}} 2 ({{ill|lt=1533|Q6443|qid=Q6443|1=1533}}){{Sfn|Tochigi City Board of Education|2014|p=21}}{{Sfn|Iwafune Town Board of Education|1974|p=14}}. According to some records, part of it was renovated in {{ill|lt=Ōei|Q1193078|qid=Q1193078|1=Ōei}} 21 ({{ill|lt=1414|Q6179|qid=Q6179|1=1414}}), and a major renovation was carried out in Tenbun 2 by {{ill|lt=Sano Toyotsuna|Q11385105|qid=Q11385105|1=Sano Toyotsuna}}, lord of {{ill|lt=Sano Castle|Q11384983|qid=Q11384983|1=Sano Castle}}{{Sfn|Murakami|1967|p=121}}. A carving of a {{ill|lt=melon|Q5881191|qid=Q5881191|1=Melon}}, said to have been embedded by the master carpenter {{ill|lt=Hidari Jingorō|Q2668220|qid=Q2668220|1=Hidari Jingorō}} at the time of construction or major renovation, remains on the upper part of a side pillar on the southwest side of the hall{{Sfn|Kazayama|1903|p=59}}{{Sfn|Murakami|1967|p=121}}.
: It is a three-bay Kasuga-zukuri structure with a cypress-bark roof{{Sfn|Tochigi City Board of Education|2014|p=21}}{{Sfn|Iwafune Town Board of Education|1974|p=14}}. There is no distinction between the worship hall and the main hall{{Sfn|Murakami|1967|p=121}}. The {{ill|lt=bracket complexes|Q7814068|qid=Q7814068|lt=to-gumi|1=Tokyō (architecture)}} above the pillars supporting the front eaves are noted for unique features not seen in other shrine buildings of the mid-to-late Muromachi period, which was key to its cultural property designation{{Sfn|Murakami|1967|p=121}}.
: On {{ill|lt=August 1|Q2788|qid=Q2788|1=August 1}}, {{ill|lt=1908|Q2056|qid=Q2056|1=1908}} ({{ill|lt=Meiji|Q3125096|qid=Q3125096|1=Meiji era}} 41), it was designated a Specially Protected Building under the then {{ill|lt=Ancient Shrines and Temples Preservation Law|Q11411552|qid=Q11411552|1=Ancient Temples and Shrines Preservation Law}} (equivalent to an {{ill|lt=Important Cultural Property|Q1188622|qid=Q1188622|1=Important Cultural Property (Japan)}} under the {{ill|lt=Law for the Protection of Cultural Properties|Q1188502|qid=Q1188502|1=Cultural Properties Protection Law}})<ref>Home Ministry Notification No. 76 of August 1, Meiji 41 (see: [{{NDLDC|2950877}} National Diet Library Digital Collection])</ref>.

=== Tochigi City Designated Natural Monument ===
* '''Shrine Grove'''
: Designated as a natural monument of {{ill|lt=Iwafune Town|Q1203561|qid=Q1203561|1=Iwafune, Tochigi}} on {{ill|lt=April 1|Q2510|qid=Q2510|1=April 1}}, {{ill|lt=1972|Q2476|qid=Q2476|1=1972}} ({{ill|lt=Shōwa|Q327567|qid=Q327567|1=Shōwa era}} 47){{Sfn|Tochigi City Board of Education|2014|p=21}}. Following the municipal merger on {{ill|lt=April 5|Q2507|qid=Q2507|1=April 5}}, {{ill|lt=2014|Q1999|qid=Q1999|1=2014}} ({{ill|lt=Heisei|Q234510|qid=Q234510|1=Heisei era}} 26), it was inherited by Tochigi City{{Sfn|Tochigi City Board of Education|2014|p=21}}.

